    "description": "This is a comparative electromagnetic calorimeter design study that involves systematically testing three different sampling configurations to determine the optimal balance between absorber and active material thicknesses. The task requires designing and simulating a tungsten-plastic scintillator sampling calorimeter with varying layer thickness ratios while maintaining constant total absorber depth, then measuring energy resolution performance across multiple beam energies to extract the stochastic term of the energy resolution function. The study specifically focuses on understanding how sampling fraction affects energy resolution in a compact, high-Z absorber calorimeter design.",
